## 3. Enrollment Data and Attrition

Reports on enrollment losses often cite different numbers (85,000, 120,000, or 160,000+). These figures represent the same trend measured at different points in time, influenced by federal grace period rules.

### 3.1 Timeline of Terminations
Under federal regulations (45 C.F.R. § 156.270), enrollees receiving advance premium tax credits are entitled to a three-month grace period for non-payment of premiums before coverage can be terminated.

| Date | Reported Terminations | Context | Source |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Jan 31, 2026** | 85,000 | Terminations recorded at the close of Open Enrollment. Includes non-renewals and failure to pay initial premiums. | Pennie (2026a) |
| **April 6, 2026** | ~120,000 | Interim figure reflecting the expiration of grace periods for January and February non-payments. | Leonard (2026) |
| **June 1, 2026** | 160,000+ | Cumulative terminations including full grace period expirations and mid-year dropouts. | Pennie (2026b) |

**Current Enrollment:** As of June 1, 2026, total active enrollment is 443,024 (Pennie, 2026b).

### 3.2 Shift in Plan Selection
Due to rising costs, there has been a measurable shift in plan selection. Enrollment in Bronze-tier plans increased by approximately 30% compared to the previous year (Pennie, 2026a). 
*   **Trade-off:** While Bronze plans have lower monthly premiums, they carry higher deductibles. The average deductible for a Bronze plan in 2026 is estimated at $7,186, compared to $5,304 for Silver plans (KFF, 2026).

